INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(2069,'subsection','sec:Bhead-ZZZZ-75','Folding Due to Under-Sampling',4,4,20);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(2070,'subsection','sec:Bhead-ZZZZ-75','Folding Due to Under-Sampling',4,4,20);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(2071,'paragraph',NULL,'<h3 class="ITS_BOOK">4-2.7  Folding Due to Under-Sampling</h3> Figure <a href="fig:samp4" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> shows the case where under-sampling leads to folding; here the sampling rate is <span class="ITS_HTML">&fnof;<sub>s</sub>=125</span> samples/sec. Once again, the top panel shows the spectrum of the continuous-time signal with spectrum lines at <span class="ITS_HTML">&plusmn; 100</span> Hz. <div class="ITS_Image"><center><img src="FILES/SP1Figures/Ch04/Fig04-10_samdem6T80.png" alt="FILES/SP1Figures/Ch04/Fig04-10_samdem6T80.png"></center><br><div class="ITS_Caption">Sampling a 100 Hz sinusoid at <span class="ITS_HTML">&fnof;<sub>s</sub> = 125</span> samples/sec.  The time-domain plot (middle) shows the samples <span class="ITS_HTML">x[n]</span> as gray dots, the original sinusoid <span class="ITS_HTML">x(t)</span> as a continuous orange line, and the reconstructed signal <span class="ITS_HTML">y(t)</span> as a dashed black line. In this case, <span class="ITS_HTML">y(t)</span> is a 25 Hz sinusoid that passes through the same sample points.</span></div></div> The discrete-time spectrum (bottom panel) is constructed by mapping <span class="ITS_HTML">&plusmn; 100</span> Hz to the two spectrum lines at <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.exe?\\hat\\omega = \\pm 2\\pi (100/f_s) = \\pm 1.6\\pi"/>, and then including all the aliases to get lines at <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="bracket" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.exe? \\begin{array}{ll} \\hat\\omega =  1.6\\pi + 2\\pi\\ell &\\qquad \\ell = 0, \\pm 1, \\pm 2, \\ldots\\\\ \\hat\\omega =  -1.6\\pi + 2\\pi\\ell &\\qquad \\ell = 0, \\pm 1, \\pm 2, \\ldots\\\\ \\end{array} "/></div> In this case, an interesting thing happens. The two frequency components between <span class="ITS_HTML">&plusmn; &pi;</span> are <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.exe?\\hat\\omega = \\pm 0.4\\pi"/>, but the one at <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.exe?\\hat\\omega = +0.4\\pi"/> is an alias of <span class="ITS_HTML">-1.6&pi;</span>. This is an example of folding. The analog frequency of the reconstructed output will be <span class="ITS_HTML">&fnof; = 0.4&pi;(&fnof;<sub>s</sub>/2&pi;) = &fnof;<sub>s</sub>/5 = 25</span> Hz.  An additional fact about folding is that the sign of the phase of the signal will be changed. If the original 100-Hz sinusoid had a phase of <span class="ITS_HTML">&phi; = +&pi;/3</span>, then the phase of the component at <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.exe?\\hat\\omega = -1.6\\pi"/> would be <span class="ITS_HTML">-&pi;/3</span>, and it follows that the phase of the aliased component at <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.exe?\\hat\\omega = +0.4\\pi"/> would also be <span class="ITS_HTML">-&pi;/3</span>. After reconstruction, the phase of <span class="ITS_HTML">y(t)</span> would be <span class="ITS_HTML">-&pi;/3</span>. It is possible to observe this &ldquo;phase-reversal&rdquo; in the middle panel of Fig. <a href="fig:samp4" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>. The input signal (solid orange line) is going down at <span class="ITS_HTML">t=0</span>, while the reconstructed output (black dashed line) is going up. What this means is that when we sample a 100 Hz sinusoid at a sampling rate of 125 samples/sec, we get the same samples that we would have gotten by sampling a 25 Hz sinusoid.',4,4,20);
